76561198047432250,Recommended,232050,13266738,"Posted: 7 December, 2014",all,Ged,"Imagine a HoMM game that is more deep than its predecessor, but made by a small dev that cares. A game in which you really need to watch over your provinces. Many different things (presented as stories with few choices) may happen. Those can either boost or hamper your chances of winning. There are also many possibilities when it comes to building types. Every province is like a small city and choosing the right buildings to build there may affect your income, population, events and happiness. Other than the gameplay I also find the story better than typical heroic fantasy boredom.On the negative side (to some gamers) there is a lot of learning to be done and I recommend reading a basic guide. The one in the game does not cover some of the more complex features."
76561198022751934,Recommended,232050,10397950,"Posted: 8 June, 2014",all,Manabender,"Eador is the first strategy game I've really been able to sink my teeth into. And that's saying something, because I seem like the kind of person to enjoy strategy games...The reason for this is because the game remains paletable throughout. I think the thing that typically drives me away from strategy games a few hours in is that, once you start to amass resources and turn those resources into troops, etc., there's so much to take care of at any one time that it's too easy to lose track of anything oreverything.Eador isn't like that. While you caneventuallyget a gigantic army, colossal empire, and a mountain of resources, the buildup to that is very slow and easy to take in. Your armies are led by heroes, which cost exponentially more for each successive one, and each hero only starts with the capacity to have three units in its army (except for one, which starts with four slots). Over time, they'll level up and be able to lead more troops.Essentially, this leads to a strategy game where the most important resource is time. Hard limits are set on just how much you can do in a single turn, so, rather than a game where the first guy to get a billion troops wins, you get a game where the guy to best optimize his time wins."
