76561198053234919,Recommended,232050,17536028,"Posted: 14 August, 2015",all,Stag,"While this game is worthwhile on a number of levels, such as the many choices of buildings to construct, the endless variety of maps that are generated, and the many different items you may find as loot, what I am most intrigued by are the continuously important choices you must make when it comes to whether or not to fight a battle.  Going up against 3 giant spiders may seem somewhat easy for an archer who has gained several levels and found a decent bow, but 8 or 9 may be overwhelming, so getting a sense of what is and is not achievable, and when, is a real skill here.  Should you decide to play at a high enough difficulty that the advice is turned off, then skillfull decisions become crucial, because it is there that the handholding is truly gone.The discovery of what unit types complement one another is also quite fun to explore, especially on the occasion when you may acquire a unit type that cannot be recruited in your own castle.  I am dying to mention some of my favorites combinations, but it is the joy of these discoveries that makes them satisfying, so I will leave it at that.True, there is still an occasional crash, but I have not had to begin a new game because of them in well over a year, maybe longer. Restarting the game lets me resume play after replaying only a single turn, so it's not much of an inconvenience.  In the end, this game keeps me coming back again and again because of its good things, and I am always delighted to discover more."
