,Not Recommended,232050,9884987,"Posted: 20 April, 2014",all,Lidhuin,"While many of the serious bugs have been resolved a year later, a few game-breaking bugs do remain (albeit the ones listed above do not).Gameplay balance remains an issue, and it inherently leads to a very grindy game.So it remains a diamond in the rough.---After almost a year, this game remains a bug-ridden hellhole, with very little tactical or strategic balance at most levels of the gameplay. I'm almost tempted to say the bugs are worse now than they were a year ago.Some bugs include:- if more than one battle of any kind occurs on the map, no other battles can occur. They immediately auto-resolve with both sides being listed as dead despite not being dead.- The AI cannot conquer any terrain where it has to fight player guards. Neither the guards will die nor will the province be conquered.Some gameplay issues include:- In campaign mode, it is entirely possible for the capitol of an AI to be guarded by 9 centaurs. Centaurs are powerful tier 2 units. If this occurs in the first or second mission, you have been given a near-impossible task, as the gameplay elements that allow you to defeat centaurs are not available until later in the game. You can, of course, surrender, and keep playing. This, and similar balance issues, remain a frustrating element of the game.- Starting units are worthless and unless you follow certain strategies or know what you're doing, you're likely to be stuck in your home province for many, many turns.All of this is incredibly sad, as the game's core concept is pretty great. The programming and game design, however, are lackluster and poor. A great game marred by poor design."
