76561198104361263,Recommended,232050,23379282,"Posted: 4 June, 2016",all,Taddy Mason,"i love eador. this or any version. i won't deny that masters of the broken world has it's flaws, but overall i love it. there are plenty of reviews out there that will tell you what can be improved about this game, so i just want to focus on the postive aspects. what i really enjoy is that you build buildings in your main province or territory to recruit troops, upgrade units, boosts production, learn spells-basically everything in the game. if you want to buy your own armor and weapons, you can build the buildings associated with it, but beyond that, as you conquer more territories and hire guards to partol and protect them from potential uprisings or invaders, you can also build more buildings in those territories to do things like hire troops, buy items and learn spells from your capital territory without having to be there. you can also construct buildings in those provinces to boost production of the different currencies and other resources across your empire.i love that the different heroes allow for pretty widely varied playstyles. the scout/archer picks people off from a distance, the warrior is a one many army, the commander boosts his troops to near hero like levels and can have the largest number of troops on the battlefield, and the mage can be a range spellcaster, a healer, a necromancer with an army of the undead or a summoner of hellish hordes. the mage class is definitely my favorite. picking one hero at the start doesn't prevent you from getting the others later on, the cost goes up more and more, but you can keep buying new heroes and making more armies.there's a huge range of enemies to fight and the battlefield itself adds extra depth to the combat. hills slow down movement but provide extra defense for melee combat and extra range for archers, forests provide cover from range attacks and hinder movement. the swamps also slow down units and reduce defense for troops unlucky enough to be in there when attacked. seemingly every enemy you come across in the story can potentially be recruited and used to fight for you. if you don't want to play for hours to unlock the better weapons, armor, monsters, etc., you can play a quick match on a custom shard against custom opponents and you'll start with all the buildings unlocked and the freedom to explore any playstyle you want."
